# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: transmission-line
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] In telecommunication, a **two-wire circuit** is characterized by supporting transmission in two directions simultaneously, as opposed to four-wire circuits, which have separate pairs for transmit and receive.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] The subscriber local loop from the telco central office are almost all two wire for analog baseband voice calls (and some digital services like ISDN), and converted to four-wire at the line card back when telephone switching was performed on baseband audio.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] Today the audio is digitized and processed completely in the digital domain upstream from the local loop.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] The reason for using two wires rather than four is simple economics—half the materials cost half as much to purchase and install.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] Note the use of the past-tense "cost," as installation of two-wire copper local loops for telephony was done primarily during the mid 20th century.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] In developing nations, wireless communications are considered to be the most cost-effective from an infrastructure perspective.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] Two-wire circuits in new installations are limited to intercom and military field telephone applications, though these too are being supplanted by modern digital communication modes.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] To communicate in both directions in the same wire pair, conversion between four-wire and two-wire was necessary, both at the telephone and at the central office.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] A hybrid coil accomplishes the conversion for both.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] At the central office, it is part of a four-wire terminating set, more often as part of a line card.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] A modern line card has no two-to-four wire conversion whatsoever; it is strictly an analog/digital interface to a system that has a completely digital and integrated signal path internally.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] Using actual wires to circuit switch a telephone call became obsolete when the crossbar switch (a mechanical system) was replaced by 4ESS electronic switches in the 1970s by the Bell System in the US.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] The old telephone hybrids of yore have been replaced by inexpensive IC chip-based components that perform the same functions at greatly reduced cost.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] When personal computing and the Internet became popular at the end of the 20th century, the inductive load of traditional hybrids became a liability for computer modem users, and remaining loading coils in subscriber lines were scrapped.
[src:transmission-line/2-wire] Different countries have different standards for telephone impedance.
[src:transmission-line/4-wire] In telecommunications, a **four-wire circuit** is a two-way circuit using two paths so arranged that the respective signals are transmitted in one direction only by one path and in the other direction by the other path.
[src:transmission-line/4-wire] The four-wire circuit gets its name from the fact that is uses four conductors to create two complete electrical circuits, one for each direction.
[src:transmission-line/4-wire] The two separate circuits (channels) allow full-duplex operation with low crosstalk.
[src:transmission-line/4-wire] In telephony a four-wire circuit was historically used to transport and switch baseband audio signals in the phone company telephone exchange before the advent of digital modulation and the electronic switching system eliminated baseband audio from the telco plant except for the local loop.
[src:transmission-line/4-wire] The local loop is a two-wire circuit for one reason only: to save copper.
[src:transmission-line/4-wire] Using half the number of copper wire conductors per circuit means that the infrastructure cost for wiring each circuit is halved.
[src:transmission-line/4-wire] Although a lower quality circuit, the local loop allows full duplex operation by using a telephone hybrid to keep near and far voice levels equivalent.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] An **acoustic transmission line** is the use of a long duct, which acts as an acoustic waveguide and is used to produce or transmit sound in an undistorted manner.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Technically it is the acoustic analog of the electrical transmission line, typically conceived as a rigid-walled duct or tube, that is long and thin relative to the wavelength of sound present in it.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The comparison between an acoustic duct and an electrical transmission line is useful in "lumped-element" modeling of acoustical systems, in which acoustic elements like volumes, tubes, pistons, and screens can be modeled as single elements in a circuit.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] With the substitution of pressure for voltage, and volume particle velocity for current, the equations are essentially the same.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Electrical transmission lines can be used to describe acoustic tubes and ducts, provided the frequency of the waves in the tube is below the critical frequency, such that they are purely planar.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Phase inversion is achieved by selecting a length of line that is equal to the quarter wavelength of the target lowest frequency.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] 1, which shows a hard boundary at one end (the speaker) and the open-ended line vent at the other.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The phase relationship between the bass driver and vent is in phase in the pass band until the frequency approaches the quarter wavelength, when the relationship reaches 90 degrees as shown.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] However, by this time the vent is producing most of the output (Fig.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Because the line is operating over several octaves with the drive unit, cone excursion is reduced, providing higher SPL's and lower distortion levels, compared with reflex and infinite baffle designs.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] where f is the sound frequency in hertz (Hz), $344$ is the speed of sound in air at 20°C in meters/second, and $\ell$ is the length of the transmission line in meters.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The complex loading of the bass drive unit demands specific Thiele-Small driver parameters to realise the full benefits of a TL design.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] However, most drive units in the marketplace are developed for the more common reflex and infinite baffle designs and are usually not suitable for TL loading.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] High efficiency bass drivers with extended low frequency ability, are usually designed to be extremely light and flexible, having very compliant suspensions.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Whilst performing well in a reflex design, these characteristics do not match the demands of a TL design.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The drive unit is effectively coupled to a long column of air which has mass.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] This lowers the resonant frequency of the drive unit, negating the need for a highly compliant device.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The introduction of the absorption materials reduces the velocity of sound through the line, as discovered by Bailey in his original work.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Bradbury published his extensive tests to determine this effect in a paper in the Journal of the Audio Engineering Society (JAES) in 1976 and his results agreed that heavily damped lines could reduce the velocity of sound by as much as 50%, although 35% is typical in medium damped lines.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Bradbury's tests were carried out using fibrous materials, typically longhaired wool and glass fibre.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] These kinds of materials, however, produce highly variable effects that are not consistently repeatable for production purposes.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] They are also liable to produce inconsistencies due to movement, climatic factors and effects over time.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] High-specification acoustic foams, developed by loudspeaker manufacturers such as PMC, with similar characteristics to longhaired wool, provide repeatable results for consistent production.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The density of the polymer, the diameter of the pores and the sculptured profiling are all specified to provide the correct absorption for each speaker model.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Quantity and position of the foam is critical to engineer a low-pass acoustic filter that provides adequate attenuation of the upper bass frequencies, whilst allowing an unimpeded path for the low bass frequencies.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The concept was termed "acoustical labyrinth" by Stromberg-Carlson Co. when used in their console radios beginning in 1936 (see Concert Grand 837G Ch= 837 Radio Stromberg-Carlson Australasia Pty | Radiomuseum).
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The Transmission line type of loudspeaker enclosure was proposed in October 1965 by Dr A.R.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Radford in *Wireless World* (p483-486) magazine.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The article postulated that energy from the rear of a driver unit could be essentially absorbed, without damping the cone's motion or superimposing internal reflections and resonance, so Bailey and Radford reasoned that the rear wave could be channeled down a long pipe.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] If the acoustic energy was absorbed, it would not be available to excite resonances.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] A pipe of sufficient length could be tapered, and stuffed so that the energy loss was almost complete, minimizing output from the open end.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] No broad consensus on the ideal taper (expanding, uniform cross-section, or contracting) has been established.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Acoustic transmission lines gained attention in their use within loudspeakers in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] In 1965, A R Bailey's article in Wireless World, “A Non-resonant Loudspeaker Enclosure Design”, detailed a working Transmission Line, which was commercialized by John Wright and partners under the brand name IMF and later TDL, and were sold by audiophile Irving M.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] A transmission line is used in loudspeaker design, to reduce time, phase and resonance related distortions, and in many designs to gain exceptional bass extension to the lower end of human hearing, and in some cases the near-infrasonic (below 20 Hz).
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] TDL's 1980s reference speaker range (now discontinued) contained models with frequency ranges of 20 Hz upwards, down to 7 Hz upwards, without needing a separate subwoofer.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] "I believe that speakers should preserve the integrity of the signal waveform and the Audio Perfectionist Journal has presented a great deal of information about the importance of time domain performance in loudspeakers.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] I’m not the only one who appreciates time- and phase-accurate speakers but I have been virtually the only advocate to speak out in print in recent years.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] In practice, the duct is folded inside a conventional shaped cabinet, so that the open end of the duct appears as a vent on the speaker cabinet.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] There are many ways in which the duct can be folded and the line is often tapered in cross section to avoid parallel internal surfaces that encourage standing waves.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Depending upon the drive unit and quantity – and various physical properties – of absorbent material, the amount of taper will be adjusted during the design process to tune the duct to remove irregularities in its response.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The internal partitioning provides substantial bracing for the entire structure, reducing cabinet flexing and colouration.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The inside faces of the duct or line, are treated with an absorbent material to provide the correct termination with frequency to load the drive unit as a TL.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] A theoretically perfect TL would absorb all frequencies entering the line from the rear of the drive unit but remains theoretical, as it would have to be infinitely long.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The physical constraints of the real world, demand that the length of the line must often be less than 4 meters before the cabinet becomes too large for any practical applications, so not all the rear energy can be absorbed by the line.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] In a realized TL, only the upper bass is TL loaded in the true sense of the term (i.e. fully absorbed); the low bass is allowed to freely radiate from the vent in the cabinet.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The line therefore effectively works as a low-pass filter, another crossover point in fact, achieved acoustically by the line and its absorbent filling.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Below this “crossover point” the low bass is loaded by the column of air formed by the length of the line.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The length is specified to reverse the phase of the rear output of the drive unit as it exits the vent.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] This energy combines with the output of the bass unit, extending its response and effectively creating a second driver.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] A duct for sound propagation also behaves like a transmission line (e.g. air conditioning duct, car muffler, ...).
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Its length may be similar to the wavelength of the sound passing through it, but the dimensions of its cross-section are normally smaller than one quarter the wavelength.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] Sound is introduced at one end of the tube by forcing the pressure across the whole cross-section to vary with time.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] An almost planar wavefront travels down the line at the speed of sound.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] When the wave reaches the end of the transmission line, behaviour depends on what is present at the end of the line.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The frequency of the pulse generated at the transducer results in a pressure null at the terminus exit (even ordered harmonic open pipe anti -resonance) resulting in effectively high acoustic impedance of the duct and low level of energy transfer.
[src:transmission-line/acoustic-transmission-line] The frequency of the pulse generated at the transducer results in neither a peak or null in which energy transfer is nominal or in keeping with typical energy dissipation with distance from the source.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] A Y-parameter matrix describes the behaviour of any linear electrical network that can be regarded as a black box with a number of ports.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] A *port* in this context is a pair of electrical terminals carrying equal and opposite currents into and out of the network, and having a particular voltage between them.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] The Y-matrix gives no information about the behaviour of the network when the currents at any port are not balanced in this way (should this be possible), nor does it give any information about the voltage between terminals not belonging to the same port.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] Typically, it is intended that each external connection to the network is between the terminals of just one port, so that these limitations are appropriate.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] For a generic multi-port network definition, it is assumed that each of the ports is allocated an integer n ranging from 1 to N, where N is the total number of ports.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] For port n, the associated Y-parameter definition is in terms of the port voltage and port current, Vn and In respectively.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] where Y is an *N* × *N* matrix the elements of which can be indexed using conventional matrix notation.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] In general the elements of the Y-parameter matrix are complex numbers and functions of frequency.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] For a one-port network, the Y-matrix reduces to a single element, being the ordinary admittance measured between the two terminals.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] The Y-parameter matrix for the two-port network is probably the most common.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] where YL is the admittance of the load connected to port two.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] where YS is the admittance of the source connected to port one.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] and ${\sqrt {z}}=({\sqrt {y}})^{-1}$ is the corresponding diagonal matrix of square roots of characteristic impedances.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] In these expressions the matrices represented by the bracketed factors commute and so, as shown above, may be written in either order.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] The above expressions will generally use complex numbers for $S_{ij}$ and $Y_{ij}$ .
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] Note that the value of $\Delta$ can become 0 for specific values of $S_{ij}$ so the division by $\Delta$ in the calculations of $Y_{ij}$ may lead to a division by 0.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] The two-port S-parameters may also be obtained from the equivalent two-port Y-parameters by means of the following expressions.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] and $Z_{0}$ is the characteristic impedance at each port (assumed the same for the two ports).
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] Conversion from Z-parameters to Y-parameters is much simpler, as the Y-parameter matrix is just the inverse of the Z-parameter matrix.
[src:transmission-line/admittance-parameters] In this case $|Z|$ is the determinant of the Z-parameter matrix.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's father, grandfather, and brother had all been associated with work on elocution and speech, and both his mother and wife were deaf, profoundly influencing Bell's life's work.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His research on hearing and speech further led him to experiment with hearing devices, which eventually culminated in his being awarded the first U.S. patent for the telephone, on March 7, 1876.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell considered his invention an intrusion on his real work as a scientist and refused to have a telephone in his study.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Many other inventions marked Bell's later life, including ground-breaking work in optical telecommunications, hydrofoils, and aeronautics.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell also had a strong influence on the National Geographic Society and its magazine while serving as its second president from 1898 to 1903.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] For *National Geographic*, Bell wrote under the pseudonym **H.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Beyond his work in engineering, Bell had a deep interest in the emerging science of heredity.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His work in this area has been called "the soundest, and most useful study of human heredity proposed in nineteenth-century America ...
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was born in Edinburgh, Scotland, on March 3, 1847, to Alexander Melville Bell, a phonetician, and Eliza Grace Bell (née Symonds).
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The family home was on South Charlotte Street in Edinburgh, where a stone inscription marks it as Bell's birthplace.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He had two brothers: Melville James Bell (1845–1870) and Edward Charles Bell (1848–1867), who both died of tuberculosis.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At age 10, however, he made a plea to his father to have a middle name like his two brothers.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] For his 11th birthday, his father acquiesced and allowed him to adopt the name "Graham", chosen out of respect for Alexander Graham, a Canadian being treated by his father who was also a family friend.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] To close relatives and friends he remained "Aleck".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell and his siblings attended a Presbyterian Church in their youth.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] As a child, Bell displayed a curiosity about his world; he gathered botanical specimens and ran experiments at an early age.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His best friend was Ben Herdman, a neighbour whose family operated a flour mill.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At the age of 12, Bell built a homemade device that combined rotating paddles with sets of nail brushes, creating a simple dehusking machine that was put into operation at the mill and used steadily for a number of years.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In return, Ben's father John Herdman gave both boys the run of a small workshop in which to "invent".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] From his early years, Bell showed a sensitive nature and a talent for art, poetry, and music that his mother encouraged.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With no formal training, he mastered the piano and became the family's pianist.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Though normally quiet and introspective, he revelled in mimicry and "voice tricks" akin to ventriloquism that entertained family guests.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was also deeply affected by his mother's gradual deafness (she began to lose her hearing when he was 12), and learned a manual finger language so he could sit at her side and tap out silently the conversations swirling around the family parlour.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He also developed a technique of speaking in clear, modulated tones directly into his mother's forehead, whereby she would hear him with reasonable clarity.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's preoccupation with his mother's deafness led him to study acoustics.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His family was long associated with the teaching of elocution: his grandfather, Alexander Bell, in London, his uncle in Dublin, and his father, in Edinburgh, were all elocutionists.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His father published a variety of works on the subject, several of which are still well known, especially *The Standard Elocutionist* (1860), which appeared in Edinburgh in 1868.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] *The Standard Elocutionist* appeared in 168 British editions and sold over 250,000 copies in the United States alone.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] It explains methods to instruct deaf-mutes (as they were then known) to articulate words and read other people's lip movements to decipher meaning.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's father taught him and his brothers not only to write Visible Speech but to identify any symbol and its accompanying sound.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell became so proficient that he became a part of his father's public demonstrations and astounded audiences with his abilities.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He could decipher Visible Speech representing virtually every language, including Latin, Scottish Gaelic, and even Sanskrit, accurately reciting written tracts without any prior knowledge of their pronunciation.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] As a young child, Bell, like his brothers, was schooled at home by his father.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At an early age, he was enrolled at the Royal High School in Edinburgh.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] But he left at age 15, having completed only the first four forms.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His school record was undistinguished, marked by absenteeism and lacklustre grades.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His main interest remained in the sciences, especially biology, while he treated other school subjects with indifference, to his father's dismay.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Upon leaving school, Bell travelled to London to live with his grandfather, Alexander Bell, on Harrington Square.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During the year he spent with his grandfather, a love of learning was born, with long hours spent in serious discussion and study.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The elder Bell took great efforts to have his young pupil learn to speak clearly and with conviction, attributes he would need to become a teacher himself.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At age 16, Bell secured a position as a "pupil-teacher" of elocution and music at Weston House Academy in Elgin, Moray, Scotland.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although enrolled as a student in Latin and Greek, he instructed classes himself in return for board and £10 per session.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The next year, he attended the University of Edinburgh, joining his brother Melville, who had enrolled there the previous year.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1868, Bell completed his matriculation exams and was accepted for admission to University College London, though he did not complete his studies, as his family emigrated to Canada in 1870 following the deaths of his brothers Edward and Melville from tuberculosis.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's father encouraged his interest in speech and, in 1863, took his sons to see a unique automaton developed by Sir Charles Wheatstone based on the earlier work of Baron Wolfgang von Kempelen.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The rudimentary "mechanical man" simulated a human voice.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was fascinated by the machine, and after he obtained a copy of von Kempelen's book, published in German, and had laboriously translated it, he and Melville built their own automaton head.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Their father, highly interested in their project, offered to pay for any supplies and spurred the boys on with the enticement of a "big prize" if they were successful.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While his brother constructed the throat and larynx, Bell tackled the more difficult task of recreating a realistic skull.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His efforts resulted in a remarkably lifelike head that could "speak", albeit only a few words.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The boys would carefully adjust the "lips" and when a bellows forced air through the windpipe, a very recognizable *Mama* ensued, to the delight of neighbours who came to see the invention.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Intrigued by the results of the automaton, Bell continued to experiment with a live subject, the family's Skye Terrier, Trouve.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After he taught it to growl continuously, Bell would reach into its mouth and manipulate the dog's lips and vocal cords to produce a crude-sounding "Ow ah oo ga ma ma".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With little convincing, visitors believed his dog could articulate "How are you, grandmama?" Indicative of his playful nature, his experiments convinced onlookers that they saw a "talking dog".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] These initial forays into experimentation with sound led Bell to undertake his first serious work on the transmission of sound, using tuning forks to explore resonance.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At age 19, Bell wrote a report on his work and sent it to philologist Alexander Ellis, a colleague of his father.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Ellis immediately wrote back indicating that the experiments were similar to existing work in Germany, and also lent Bell a copy of Hermann von Helmholtz's work, *The Sensations of Tone as a Physiological Basis for the Theory of Music*.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Dismayed to find that groundbreaking work had already been undertaken by Helmholtz, who had conveyed vowel sounds by means of a similar tuning fork "contraption", Bell pored over the book.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1865, when the Bell family moved to London, Bell returned to Weston House as an assistant master and, in his spare hours, continued experiments on sound using a minimum of laboratory equipment.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell concentrated on experimenting with electricity to convey sound and later installed a telegraph wire from his room in Somerset College to that of a friend.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Throughout late 1867, his health faltered mainly through exhaustion.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His brother Edward was similarly affected by tuberculosis.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While Bell recovered (by then referring to himself in correspondence as "A.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell") and served the next year as an instructor at Somerset College, Bath, England, his brother's condition deteriorated.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Upon his brother's death, Bell returned home in 1867.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With aspirations to obtain a degree at University College London, Bell considered his next years preparation for the degree examinations, devoting his spare time to studying.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Helping his father in Visible Speech demonstrations and lectures brought Bell to Susanna E.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Hull's private school for the deaf in South Kensington, London.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His first two pupils were deaf-mute girls who made remarkable progress under his tutelage.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While Melville seemed to achieve success on many fronts, including opening his own elocution school, applying for a patent on an invention, and starting a family, Bell continued as a teacher.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In May 1870, Melville died from complications of tuberculosis, causing a family crisis.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His father had also experienced a debilitating illness earlier in life and been restored to health by convalescence in Newfoundland.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's parents embarked upon a long-planned move when they realized that their remaining son was also sickly.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Acting decisively, Alexander Melville Bell asked Bell to arrange for the sale of all the family property, conclude all his brother's affairs (Bell took on his last student, curing a pronounced lisp), and join his father and mother in setting out for Canada.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Reluctantly, Bell also had to conclude a relationship with Marie Eccleston, who, as he had surmised, was not prepared to leave England with him.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1870, 23-year-old Bell travelled with his parents and his brother's widow, Caroline Margaret Ottaway, to Paris, Ontario, to stay with Thomas Henderson, a Baptist minister and family friend.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bells soon purchased a farm of 10.5 acres (4.2 ha) at Tutelo Heights (now called Tutela Heights), near Brantford, Ontario.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The property consisted of an orchard, large farmhouse, stable, pigsty, hen-house, and a carriage house, which bordered the Grand River.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At the homestead, Bell set up a workshop in the converted carriage house near what he called his "dreaming place", a large hollow nestled in trees at the back of the property above the river.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Despite his frail condition upon arriving in Canada, Bell found the climate and environs to his liking and rapidly improved.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He continued his interest in the study of the human voice, and when he discovered the Six Nations Reserve across the river at Onondaga, learned the Mohawk language and translated its unwritten vocabulary into Visible Speech symbols.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] For his work, Bell was awarded the title of Honorary Chief and participated in a ceremony where he donned a Mohawk headdress and danced traditional dances.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After setting up his workshop, Bell continued experiments based on Helmholtz's work with electricity and sound.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He also modified a melodeon (a type of pump organ) to transmit its music electrically over a distance.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Once the family was settled, Bell and his father made plans to establish a teaching practice and in 1871, he accompanied his father to Montreal, where Melville was offered a position to teach his System of Visible Speech.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's father was invited by Sarah Fuller, principal of the Boston School for Deaf Mutes (later to become the public Horace Mann School for the Deaf) to introduce the Visible Speech System by providing training for Fuller's instructors, but he declined the post in favour of his son.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Travelling to Boston in April 1871, Bell proved successful in training the school's instructors.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He was asked to repeat the programme at the American Asylum for Deaf-mutes in Hartford, Connecticut, and the Clarke School for the Deaf in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Returning home to Brantford after six months abroad, Bell continued his experiments with his "harmonic telegraph".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The basic concept behind his device was that messages could be sent through a single wire if each was transmitted at a different pitch, but work on both the transmitter and receiver was needed.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Unsure of his future, he contemplated returning to London to complete his studies, but decided to return to Boston as a teacher.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His father helped him set up his private practice by contacting Gardiner Greene Hubbard, the president of the Clarke School for the Deaf for a recommendation.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Teaching his father's system, in October 1872, Alexander Bell opened his "School of Vocal Physiology and Mechanics of Speech" in Boston, which attracted a large number of deaf pupils, with his first class numbering 30 students.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While he was working as a private tutor, one of his pupils was Helen Keller, who came to him as a young child unable to see, hear, or speak.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] She later said that Bell dedicated his life to the penetration of that "inhuman silence which separates and estranges".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1893, Keller performed the sod-breaking ceremony for the construction of Bell's new Volta Bureau, dedicated to "the increase and diffusion of knowledge relating to the deaf".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1891, Bell established the American Association for the Promotion of the Teaching of Speech to the Deaf (AAPTSD) in New York and endowed the organization with a gift of $25,000.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While endorsing the teaching of speech to the deaf, Bell remained neutral as to whether oral, manual or a combination of the three methods would best benefit the student.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Throughout his life, Bell sought to assimilate the deaf and hard of hearing with the broader population.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He encouraged speech therapy and lip-reading as well as sign language.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He outlined this in an 1898 paper detailing his belief that, with resources and effort, the deaf could be taught to read lips and speak (known as oralism), enabling their integration with wider society.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Members of the Deaf community have criticized Bell for supporting lip-reading over the use of sign language.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1872, Bell became professor of Vocal Physiology and Elocution at the Boston University School of Oratory.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During this period, he alternated between Boston and Brantford, spending summers in his Canadian home.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At Boston University, Bell was "swept up" by the excitement engendered by the many scientists and inventors living in the city.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He continued his research in sound and endeavoured to find a way to transmit musical notes and articulate speech, but although absorbed by his experiments, he found it difficult to devote enough time to experimentation.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With days and evenings occupied by his teaching and private classes, Bell began to stay awake late into the night, running experiment after experiment in rented facilities at his boarding house.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Keeping "night owl" hours, he worried that his work would be discovered and took great pains to lock up his notebooks and laboratory equipment.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell had a specially made table where he could place his notes and equipment inside a locking cover.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His health deteriorated as he had severe headaches.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Returning to Boston in autumn 1873, Bell made a far-reaching decision to concentrate on his experiments in sound.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Giving up his lucrative private Boston practice, Bell retained only two students, six-year-old "Georgie" Sanders, deaf from birth, and 15-year-old Mabel Hubbard.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Each played an important role in the next developments.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Georgie's father, Thomas Sanders, a wealthy businessman, offered Bell a place to stay in nearby Salem with Georgie's grandmother, complete with a room to "experiment".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although the offer was made by Georgie's mother and followed the year-long arrangement in 1872 where her son and his nurse had moved to quarters next to Bell's boarding house, it was clear that Mr.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The arrangement was for teacher and student to continue their work together, with free room and board thrown in.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Mabel was a bright, attractive girl ten years Bell's junior who became the object of his affection.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Having lost her hearing after a near-fatal bout of scarlet fever close to her fifth birthday, she had learned to read lips but her father, Gardiner Greene Hubbard, Bell's benefactor and personal friend, wanted her to work directly with her teacher.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By 1874, Bell's initial work on the harmonic telegraph had entered a formative stage, with progress made both at his new Boston "laboratory" (a rented facility) and at his family home in Canada a big success.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While working that summer in Brantford, Bell experimented with a "phonautograph", a pen-like machine that could draw shapes of sound waves on smoked glass by tracing their vibrations.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell thought it might be possible to generate undulating electrical currents that would correspond to sound waves.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He also believed that he would be able to convert the undulating currents back into sound by tuning multiple metal reeds to different frequencies.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] But he had no working model to demonstrate the feasibility of these ideas.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1874, telegraph message traffic was rapidly expanding and, in the words of Western Union President William Orton, had become "the nervous system of commerce".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Orton had contracted with inventors Thomas Edison and Elisha Gray to find a way to send multiple telegraph messages on each telegraph line to avoid the great cost of constructing new lines.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] When Bell mentioned to Gardiner Hubbard and Thomas Sanders that he was working on a method of sending multiple tones on a telegraph wire using a multi-reed device, the two began to financially support Bell's experiments.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Patent matters were handled by Hubbard's patent attorney, Anthony Pollok.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In March 1875, Bell and Pollok visited the scientist Joseph Henry, then the director of the Smithsonian Institution, to ask his advice on the electrical multi-reed apparatus that Bell hoped would transmit the human voice by telegraph.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Henry said Bell had "the germ of a great invention".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] When Bell said that he lacked the necessary knowledge, Henry replied, "Get it!" That declaration greatly encouraged Bell to keep trying, even though he had neither the equipment needed to continue his experiments nor the ability to create a working model of his ideas.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] But a chance meeting in 1874 between Bell and Thomas A.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Watson, an experienced electrical designer and mechanic at the electrical machine shop of Charles Williams, changed that.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With financial support from Sanders and Hubbard, Bell hired Watson as his assistant, and the two experimented with acoustic telegraphy.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On June 2, 1875, Watson accidentally plucked one of the reeds and Bell, at the receiving end of the wire, heard the reed's overtones that would be necessary for transmitting speech.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] That demonstrated to Bell that only one reed or armature was necessary, not multiple reeds.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This led to the "gallows" sound-powered telephone, which could transmit indistinct, voice-like sounds, but not clear speech.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1875, Bell developed an acoustic telegraph and drew up a patent application for it.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Meanwhile, Elisha Gray was also experimenting with acoustic telegraphy and thought of a way to transmit speech using a water transmitter.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On February 14, 1876, Gray filed a caveat with the U.S.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Patent Office for a telephone design that used a water transmitter.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] That same morning, Bell's lawyer filed Bell's application with the patent office.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] There is considerable debate about who arrived first and Gray later challenged the primacy of Bell's patent.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was in Boston on February 14 and did not arrive in Washington until February 26.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Patent Office issued Bell patent 174,465.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On March 10, Bell succeeded in getting his telephone to work, using a liquid transmitter similar to Gray's design.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Vibration of the diaphragm caused a needle to vibrate in the water, varying the electrical resistance in the circuit.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Watson—Come here—I want to see you" into the liquid transmitter, Watson, listening at the receiving end in an adjoining room, heard the words clearly.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After March 1876, Bell focused on improving the electromagnetic telephone and never used Gray's liquid transmitter in public demonstrations or commercial use.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The examiner raised the question of priority for the variable resistance feature of the telephone before approving Bell's patent application.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He told Bell that his claim for the variable resistance feature was also described in Gray's caveat.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell pointed to a variable resistance device in his previous application in which he described a cup of mercury, not water.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He had filed the mercury application at the patent office on February 25, 1875, long before Gray described the water device.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In addition, Gray abandoned his caveat, and because he did not contest Bell's priority, the examiner approved Bell's patent on March 3, 1876.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Gray had reinvented the variable resistance telephone, but Bell was the first to write down the idea and test it in a telephone.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The patent examiner, Zenas Fisk Wilber, later stated in an affidavit that he was an alcoholic who was much in debt to Bell's lawyer, Marcellus Bailey, with whom he had served in the Civil War.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He said he had shown Bailey Gray's patent caveat.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Wilber also said (after Bell arrived in Washington D.C. from Boston) that he showed Bell Gray's caveat and that Bell paid him $100 (equivalent to $2,900 in 2025).
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell said they discussed the patent only in general terms, although in a letter to Gray, Bell admitted that he learned some of the technical details.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell denied in an affidavit that he ever gave Wilber any money.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On March 10, 1876, Bell used "the instrument" in Boston to call Thomas Watson who was in another room but out of earshot.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Watson, come here – I want to see you" and Watson soon appeared at his side.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Continuing his experiments in Brantford, Bell brought home a working model of his telephone.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On August 3, 1876, from the telegraph office in Brantford, Bell sent a telegram to the village of Mount Pleasant four miles (six kilometres) away, indicating that he was ready.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He made a telephone call via telegraph wires and faint voices were heard replying.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The following night, he amazed guests as well as his family with a call between the Bell Homestead and the office of the Dominion Telegraph Company in Brantford along an improvised wire strung up along telegraph lines and fences, and laid through a tunnel.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This time, guests at the household distinctly heard people in Brantford reading and singing.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The third test, on August 10, 1876, was made via the telegraph line between Brantford and Paris, Ontario, eight miles (thirteen kilometres) away.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This test is said by many sources to be the "world's first long-distance call".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] It proved that the telephone could work over long distances, at least as a one-way call.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The first two-way (reciprocal) conversation over a line occurred between Cambridge and Boston (roughly 2.5 miles) on October 9, 1876.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During that conversation, Bell was on Kilby Street in Boston and Watson was at the offices of the Walworth Manufacturing Company.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell and his partners, Hubbard and Sanders, offered to sell the patent outright to Western Union for $100,000, equal to $3,023,438 today, but it did not work (according to an apocryphal story, the president of Western Union balked, countering that the telephone was nothing but a toy).
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Two years later, he told colleagues that if he could get the patent for $25 million (equal to $834,051,724 today), he would consider it a bargain.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By then, the Bell company no longer wanted to sell the patent.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's investors became millionaires while he fared well from residuals and at one point had assets of nearly $1 million.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell began a series of public demonstrations and lectures to introduce the new invention to the scientific community as well as the general public.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] A short time later, his demonstration of an early telephone prototype at the 1876 Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia brought the telephone to international attention.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Influential visitors to the exhibition included Emperor Pedro II of Brazil.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] One of the judges at the Exhibition, Sir William Thomson (later Lord Kelvin), a renowned Scottish scientist, described the telephone as "the greatest by far of all the marvels of the electric telegraph".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On January 14, 1878, at Osborne House, on the Isle of Wight, Bell demonstrated the device to Queen Victoria, placing calls to Cowes, Southampton, and London.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] These were the first publicly witnessed long-distance telephone calls in the UK.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The queen found the process "quite extraordinary" although the sound was "rather faint".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] She later asked to buy the equipment that was used, but Bell offered to make "a set of telephones" specifically for her.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bell Telephone Company was created in 1877, and by 1886, more than 150,000 people in the U.S. owned telephones.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell Company engineers made numerous other improvements to the telephone, which emerged as one of the most successful products ever.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1879, the company acquired Edison's patents for the carbon microphone from Western Union.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This made the telephone practical for longer distances, and it was no longer necessary to shout to be heard at the receiving telephone.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Pedro II of Brazil was the first person to buy stock in the Bell Telephone Company.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] One of the first telephones in a private residence was installed in his palace in Petrópolis, his summer retreat forty miles (sixty-four kilometres) from Rio de Janeiro.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In January 1915, Bell made the first ceremonial transcontinental telephone call.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Calling from the AT&T head office at 15 Dey Street in New York City, Bell was heard by Thomas Watson at 333 Grant Avenue in San Francisco.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] As is sometimes common in scientific discoveries, simultaneous developments occurred, as evidenced by a number of inventors who were at work on the telephone.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Over 18 years, the Bell Telephone Company faced 587 court challenges to its patents, including five that went to the U.S.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Supreme Court, but none was successful in establishing priority over Bell's original patent, and the Bell Telephone Company never lost a case that had proceeded to a final trial stage.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's laboratory notes and family letters were the key to establishing a long lineage to his experiments.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bell company lawyers successfully fought off myriad lawsuits generated initially around the challenges by Elisha Gray and Amos Dolbear.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In personal correspondence to Bell, both Gray and Dolbear had acknowledged his prior work, which considerably weakened their later claims.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On January 13, 1887, the U.S. government moved to annul the patent issued to Bell on the grounds of fraud and misrepresentation.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After a series of decisions and reversals, the Bell company won a decision in the Supreme Court, though a couple of the original claims from the lower court cases were left undecided.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By the time the trial had wound its way through nine years of legal battles, the U.S. prosecuting attorney had died and the two Bell patents (No.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] 186,787, dated January 30, 1877) were no longer in effect, although the presiding judges agreed to continue the proceedings due to the case's importance as a precedent.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With a change in administration and charges of conflict of interest (on both sides) arising from the original trial, the U.S. attorney general dropped the lawsuit on November 30, 1897, leaving several issues undecided on the merits.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During a deposition filed for the 1887 trial, Italian inventor Antonio Meucci also claimed to have created the first working model of a telephone in Italy in 1834.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1886, in the first of three cases in which he was involved, Meucci took the stand as a witness in hope of establishing his invention's priority.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Meucci's testimony was disputed due to lack of material evidence for his inventions, as his working models were purportedly lost at the laboratory of American District Telegraph (ADT) of New York, which was incorporated as a subsidiary of Western Union in 1901.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Meucci's work, like that of many other inventors of the period, was based on earlier acoustic principles and, despite evidence of earlier experiments, the final case involving Meucci was eventually dropped upon Meucci's death.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] But due to the efforts of Congressman Vito Fossella, on June 11, 2002, the U.S.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] House of Representatives stated that Meucci's "work in the invention of the telephone should be acknowledged".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This did not put an end to the still contentious issue.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Some modern scholars do not agree that Bell's work on the telephone was influenced by Meucci's inventions.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The value of Bell's patent was acknowledged throughout the world, and patent applications were made in most major countries.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] When Bell delayed the German patent application, the electrical firm Siemens & Halske set up a rival manufacturer of Bell telephones under its own patent.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Siemens produced near-identical copies of the Bell telephone without having to pay royalties.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The establishment of the International Bell Telephone Company in Brussels, Belgium, in 1880, as well as a series of agreements in other countries eventually consolidated a global telephone operation.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The strain put on Bell by his constant appearances in court, necessitated by the legal battles, eventually resulted in his resignation from the company.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On July 11, 1877, a few days after the Bell Telephone Company was established, Bell married Mabel Hubbard (1857–1923) at the Hubbard estate in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His wedding present to his bride was to turn over 1,487 of his 1,497 shares in the newly formed Bell Telephone Company.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Shortly thereafter, the newly-weds embarked on a year-long honeymoon in Europe.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During that excursion, Bell took a handmade model of his telephone with him, making it a "working holiday".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The courtship had begun years earlier; however, Bell waited until he was more financially secure before marrying.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although the telephone appeared to be an "instant" success, it was not initially a profitable venture and Bell's main sources of income were from lectures until after 1897.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] One unusual request exacted by his fiancée was that he use "Alec" rather than the family's earlier familiar name of "Aleck".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] From 1876, he would sign his name "Alec Bell".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bell family home was in Cambridge, Massachusetts, until 1880 when Bell's father-in-law bought a house in Washington, D.C.; in 1882 he bought a home in the same city for Bell's family, so they could be with him while he attended to the numerous court cases involving patent disputes.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was a British subject throughout his early life in Scotland and later in Canada until 1882 when he became a naturalized citizen of the United States.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1915, he characterized his status as: "I am not one of those hyphenated Americans who claim allegiance to two countries." Despite this declaration, Bell has been proudly claimed as a "native son" by all three countries he resided in: the United States, Canada, and the United Kingdom.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By 1885, a new summer retreat was contemplated.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] That summer, the Bells had a vacation on Cape Breton Island in Nova Scotia, Canada, spending time at the small village of Baddeck.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Returning in 1886, Bell started building an estate on a point across from Baddeck, overlooking Bras d'Or Lake.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By 1889, a large house, christened *The Lodge* was completed and two years later, a larger complex of buildings, including a new laboratory, were begun that the Bells would name Beinn Bhreagh (Gaelic: *Beautiful Mountain*) after Bell's ancestral Scottish Highlands.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell also built the Bell Boatyard on the estate, employing up to 40 people building experimental craft as well as wartime lifeboats and workboats for the Royal Canadian Navy and pleasure craft for the Bell family.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He was an enthusiastic boater, and Bell and his family sailed or rowed a long series of vessels on Bras d'Or Lake, ordering additional vessels from the H.W.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Embree and Sons boatyard in Port Hawkesbury, Nova Scotia.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In his final, and some of his most productive years, Bell split his residency between Washington, D.C., where he and his family initially resided for most of the year, and Beinn Bhreagh, where they spent increasing amounts of time.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Until the end of his life, Bell and his family would alternate between the two homes, but *Beinn Bhreagh* would, over the next 30 years, become more than a summer home as Bell became so absorbed in his experiments that his annual stays lengthened.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Both Mabel and Bell became immersed in the Baddeck community and were accepted by the villagers as "their own".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bells were still in residence at *Beinn Bhreagh* when the Halifax Explosion occurred on December 6, 1917.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Mabel and Bell mobilized the community to help victims in Halifax.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although Alexander Graham Bell is most often associated with the invention of the telephone, his interests were extremely varied.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] According to one of his biographers, Charlotte Gray, Bell's work ranged "unfettered across the scientific landscape" and he often went to bed voraciously reading the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, scouring it for new areas of interest.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The range of Bell's inventive genius is represented only in part by the 18 patents granted in his name alone and the 12 he shared with his collaborators.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] These included 14 for the telephone and telegraph, four for the photophone, one for the phonograph, five for aerial vehicles, four for "hydroairplanes", and two for selenium cells.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's inventions spanned a wide range of interests and included a metal jacket to assist in breathing, the audiometer to detect minor hearing problems, a device to locate icebergs, investigations on how to separate salt from seawater, and work on finding alternative fuels.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell worked extensively in medical research and invented techniques for teaching speech to the deaf.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During his Volta Laboratory period, Bell and his associates considered impressing a magnetic field on a record as a means of reproducing sound.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although the trio briefly experimented with the concept, they could not develop a workable prototype.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] They abandoned the idea, never realizing they had glimpsed a basic principle which would one day find its application in the tape recorder, the hard disc and floppy disc drive, and other magnetic media.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's own home used a primitive form of air conditioning, in which fans blew currents of air across great blocks of ice.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He also anticipated modern concerns with fuel shortages and industrial pollution.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Methane gas, he reasoned, could be produced from the waste of farms and factories.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At his Canadian estate in Nova Scotia, he experimented with composting toilets and devices to capture water from the atmosphere.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In a magazine article published in 1917, he reflected on the possibility of using solar energy to heat houses.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell and his assistant Charles Sumner Tainter jointly invented a wireless telephone, named a photophone, which allowed for the transmission of both sounds and normal human conversations on a beam of light.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Both men later became full associates in the Volta Laboratory Association.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On June 21, 1880, Bell's assistant transmitted a wireless voice telephone message a considerable distance, from the roof of the Franklin School in Washington, D.C., to Bell at the window of his laboratory, some 700 feet (213 m) away, 19 years before the first voice radio transmissions.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell believed the photophone's principles were his life's "greatest achievement", telling a reporter shortly before his death that the photophone was "the greatest invention [I have] ever made, greater than the telephone".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The photophone was a precursor to the fiber-optic communication systems which achieved popular worldwide usage in the 1980s.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Its master patent was issued in December 1880, many decades before the photophone's principles came into popular use.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell is also credited with developing one of the early versions of a metal detector through the use of an induction balance, after the shooting of U.S.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] According to some accounts, the metal detector worked flawlessly in tests but did not find Guiteau's bullet, partly because the metal bed frame on which the President was lying disturbed the instrument, resulting in static.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Garfield's surgeons, led by self-appointed chief physician Doctor Willard Bliss, were sceptical of the device, and ignored Bell's requests to move the President to a bed not fitted with metal springs.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Alternatively, although Bell had detected a slight sound on his first test, the bullet may have been lodged too deeply to be detected by the crude apparatus.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's own detailed account, presented to the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 1882, differs in several particulars from most of the many and varied versions now in circulation, by concluding that extraneous metal was not to blame for failure to locate the bullet.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Perplexed by the peculiar results he had obtained during an examination of Garfield, Bell "proceeded to the Executive Mansion the next morning ... to ascertain from the surgeons whether they were perfectly sure that all metal had been removed from the neighborhood of the bed.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] It was then recollected that underneath the horse-hair mattress on which the President lay was another mattress composed of steel wires.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Upon obtaining a duplicate, the mattress was found to consist of a sort of net of woven steel wires, with large meshes.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The March 1906 *Scientific American* article by American pioneer William E.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Meacham explained the basic principle of hydrofoils and hydroplanes.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell considered the invention of the hydroplane as a very significant achievement.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Based on information gained from that article, he began to sketch concepts of what is now called a hydrofoil boat.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] "Casey" Baldwin began hydrofoil experimentation in the summer of 1908 as a possible aid to airplane takeoff from water.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Baldwin studied the work of the Italian inventor Enrico Forlanini and began testing models.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This led him and Bell to the development of practical hydrofoil watercraft.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During his world tour of 1910–11, Bell and Baldwin met with Forlanini in France.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] They had rides in the Forlanini hydrofoil boat over Lake Maggiore.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Baldwin described it as being as smooth as flying.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On returning to Baddeck, a number of initial concepts were built as experimental models, including the *Dhonnas Beag* (Scottish Gaelic for 'little devil'), the first self-propelled Bell-Baldwin hydrofoil.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The experimental boats were essentially proof-of-concept prototypes that culminated in the more substantial HD-4, powered by Renault engines.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] A top speed of 54 miles per hour (87 km/h) was achieved, with the hydrofoil exhibiting rapid acceleration, good stability, and steering, along with the ability to take waves without difficulty.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell hired Walter Pinaud, a Sydney yacht designer and builder as well as the proprietor of Pinaud's Yacht Yard in Westmount, Nova Scotia, to work on the pontoons of the HD-4.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Pinaud soon took over the boatyard at Bell Laboratories on Beinn Bhreagh, Bell's estate near Baddeck, Nova Scotia.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Pinaud's experience in boatbuilding enabled him to make useful design changes to the HD-4.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After the First World War, work began again on the HD-4.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Navy permitted him to obtain two 350-horsepower (260-kilowatt) engines in July 1919.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On September 9, 1919, the HD-4 set a world marine speed record of 70.86 miles per hour (114.04 kilometres per hour), a record which stood for one year.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1891, Bell had begun experiments to develop motor-powered heavier-than-air aircraft.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The AEA was first formed as Bell shared the vision to fly with his wife, who advised him to seek "young" help as Bell was at the age of 60.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1898, Bell experimented with tetrahedral box kites and wings constructed of multiple compound tetrahedral kites covered in maroon silk.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The tetrahedral wings were named *Cygnet* I, II, and III, and were flown both unmanned and manned (*Cygnet I* crashed during a flight carrying Selfridge) in the period from 1907 to 1912.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Some of Bell's kites are on display at the Alexander Graham Bell National Historic Site.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was a supporter of aerospace engineering research through the Aerial Experiment Association (AEA), officially formed at Baddeck, Nova Scotia, in October 1907 at the suggestion of his wife Mabel and with her financial support after the sale of some of her real estate.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The AEA was headed by Bell and the founding members were four young men: American Glenn H.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Federal government and one of the few people in the army who believed that aviation was the future; Frederick W.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Baldwin, the first Canadian and first British subject to pilot a public flight in Hammondsport, New York; and J.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] McCurdy–Baldwin and McCurdy being new engineering graduates from the University of Toronto.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The AEA's work progressed to heavier-than-air machines, applying their knowledge of kites to gliders.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Moving to Hammondsport, the group then designed and built the *Red Wing*, framed in bamboo and covered in red silk and powered by a small air-cooled engine.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On March 12, 1908, over Keuka Lake, the biplane lifted off on the first public flight in North America.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The innovations that were incorporated into this design included a cockpit enclosure and tail rudder (later variations on the original design would add ailerons as a means of control).
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] One of the AEA's inventions, a practical wingtip form of the aileron, was to become a standard component on all aircraft.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The *White Wing* and *June Bug* were to follow and by the end of 1908, over 150 flights without mishap had been accomplished.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] However, the AEA had depleted its initial reserves and only a $15,000 grant from Mrs.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell allowed it to continue with experiments.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Selfridge had also become the first person killed in a powered heavier-than-air flight in a crash of the Wright Flyer at Fort Myer, Virginia, on September 17, 1908.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Their final aircraft design, the *Silver Dart*, embodied all of the advancements found in the earlier machines.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On February 23, 1909, Bell was present as the *Silver Dart* flown by J.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] McCurdy from the frozen ice of Bras d'Or made the first aircraft flight in Canada.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell had worried that the flight was too dangerous and had arranged for a doctor to be on hand.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With the successful flight, the AEA disbanded and the *Silver Dart* would revert to Baldwin and McCurdy, who began the Canadian Aerodrome Company and would later demonstrate the aircraft to the Canadian Army.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell, along with many members of the scientific community at the time, took an interest in the popular science of heredity which grew out of the publication of Charles Darwin's book *On the Origin of Species* in 1859.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] On his estate in Nova Scotia, Bell conducted meticulously recorded breeding experiments with rams and ewes.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Over the course of more than 30 years, Bell sought to produce a breed of sheep with multiple nipples that would bear twins.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He specifically wanted to see if selective breeding could produce sheep with four functional nipples with enough milk for twin lambs.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] This interest in animal breeding caught the attention of scientists focused on the study of heredity and genetics in humans.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In November 1883, Bell presented a paper at a meeting of the National Academy of Sciences titled *Upon the Formation of a Deaf Variety of the Human Race*.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The paper is a compilation of data on the hereditary aspects of deafness.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's research indicated that a hereditary tendency toward deafness, as indicated by the possession of deaf relatives, was an important element in determining the production of deaf offspring.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He noted that the proportion of deaf children born to deaf parents was many times greater than the proportion of deaf children born to the general population.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In the paper, Bell delved into social commentary and discussed hypothetical public policies to bring an end to deafness.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He also criticized educational practices that segregated deaf children rather than integrating them fully into mainstream classrooms.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] A review of Bell's *Memoir upon the Formation of a Deaf Variety of the Human Race* appearing in an 1885 issue of the *American Annals of the Deaf and Dumb* states that "Dr.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Historians have noted that Bell explicitly opposed laws regulating marriage, and never mentioned sterilization in any of his writings.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Even after Bell agreed to engage with scientists conducting eugenic research, he consistently refused to support public policy that limited the rights or privileges of the deaf.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's interest and research on heredity attracted the interest of Charles Davenport, a Harvard professor and head of the Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1906, Davenport, who was also the founder of the American Breeder's Association, approached Bell about joining a new committee on eugenics chaired by David Starr Jordan.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1910, Davenport opened the Eugenics Records office at Cold Spring Harbor.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] To give the organization scientific credibility, Davenport set up a Board of Scientific Directors naming Bell as chairman.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Other members of the board included Luther Burbank, Roswell H.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1921, a Second International Congress of Eugenics was held in New York at the Museum of Natural History and chaired by Davenport.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Although Bell did not present any research or speak as part of the proceedings, he was named as honorary president as a means to attract other scientists to attend the event.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] A summary of the event notes that Bell was a "pioneering investigator in the field of human heredity".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell died of complications arising from diabetes on August 2, 1922, at his private estate in Cape Breton, Nova Scotia, at age 75.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell had also been affected by pernicious anemia.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] His last view of the land he had inhabited was by moonlight on his mountain estate at 2:00 a.m.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] While tending to him after his long illness, Mabel, his wife, whispered, "Don't leave me." By way of reply, Bell signed "no...", lost consciousness, and died shortly after.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] On learning of Bell's death, the Canadian Prime Minister, Mackenzie King, cabled Mrs.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's coffin was constructed of Beinn Bhreagh pine by his laboratory staff, lined with the same red silk fabric used in his tetrahedral kite experiments.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Upon the conclusion of Bell's funeral, for one minute at 6:25 p.m.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Eastern Time, "every phone on the continent of North America was silenced in honor of the man who had given to mankind the means for direct communication at a distance".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Alexander Graham Bell was buried atop Beinn Bhreagh mountain, on his estate where he had resided increasingly for the last 35 years of his life, overlooking Bras d'Or Lake.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He was survived by his wife Mabel, his two daughters, Elsie May and Marian, and nine of his grandchildren.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Honours and tributes flowed to Bell in increasing numbers as his invention became ubiquitous and his personal fame grew.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell received numerous honorary degrees from colleges and universities to the point that the requests almost became burdensome.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] During his life, he also received dozens of major awards, medals, and other tributes.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] These included statuary monuments to both him and the new form of communication his telephone created, including the Bell Telephone Memorial erected in his honour in *Alexander Graham Bell Gardens* in Brantford, Ontario, in 1917.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] A number of historic sites and other marks commemorate Bell in North America and Europe, including the first telephone companies in the United States and Canada.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1880, Bell received the Volta Prize with a purse of 50,000 French francs (approximately US$350,000 in today's currency) for the invention of the telephone from the French government.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Among the luminaries who judged were Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The Volta Prize was conceived by Napoleon III in 1852, and named in honour of Alessandro Volta, with Bell becoming the second recipient of the grand prize in its history.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The Volta Laboratory became an experimental facility devoted to scientific discovery, and the very next year it improved Edison's phonograph by substituting wax for tinfoil as the recording medium and incising the recording rather than indenting it, key upgrades that Edison himself later adopted.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In partnership with Gardiner Greene Hubbard, Bell helped establish the publication *Science* during the early 1880s.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1898, Bell was elected as the second president of the National Geographic Society, serving until 1903, and was primarily responsible for the extensive use of illustrations, including photography, in the magazine.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He also served for many years as a Regent of the Smithsonian Institution (1898–1922).
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He was one of the founders of the American Institute of Electrical Engineers in 1884 and served as its president from 1891 to 1892.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell was later awarded the AIEE's Edison Medal in 1914 "For meritorious achievement in the invention of the telephone".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The *bel* (B) and the smaller *decibel* (dB) are units of measurement of sound pressure level (SPL) invented by Bell Labs and named after him.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Since 1976, the IEEE's Alexander Graham Bell Medal has been awarded to honour outstanding contributions in the field of telecommunications.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1936, the US Patent Office declared Bell first on its list of the country's greatest inventors, leading to the US Post Office issuing a commemorative stamp honouring Bell in 1940 as part of its 'Famous Americans Series'.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The First Day of Issue ceremony was held on October 28 in Boston, Massachusetts, the city where Bell spent considerable time on research and working with the deaf.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The Bell stamp became very popular and sold out in little time.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The stamp became, and remains to this day, the most valuable one of the series.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The 150th anniversary of Bell's birth in 1997 was marked by a special issue of commemorative £1 banknotes from the Royal Bank of Scotland.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Additionally, the Government of Canada honoured Bell in 1997 with a C$100 gold coin, in tribute also to the 150th anniversary of his birth, and with a silver dollar coin in 2009 in honour of the 100th anniversary of flight in Canada.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] That first flight was made by an airplane designed under Dr.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's image, and also those of his many inventions have graced paper money, coinage, and postal stamps in numerous countries worldwide for many dozens of years.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Alexander Graham Bell was ranked 57th among the 100 Greatest Britons (2002) in an official BBC nationwide poll, and among the Top Ten Greatest Canadians (2004), and the 100 Greatest Americans (2005).
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 2006, Bell was also named as one of the 10 greatest Scottish scientists in history after having been listed in the National Library of Scotland's 'Scottish Science Hall of Fame'.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's name is still widely known and used as part of the names of dozens of educational institutes, corporate namesakes, street and place names around the world.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Popov's work as a teacher at a Russian naval school led him to explore high-frequency electrical phenomena.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] On 7 May 1895, he presented a paper on a wireless lightning detector he had built that worked via using a coherer to detect radio noise from lightning strikes.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] This day is celebrated today in Russia as Radio Day.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In a 24 March 1896 demonstration, he transmitted radio signals 250 meters between different campus buildings in St.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] His work was based on that of another physicist, Oliver Lodge, and contemporaneous with the work of Guglielmo Marconi.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Born in the town of Krasnoturinsk, Sverdlovsk Oblast, in the Urals as the son of a priest, he became interested in natural sciences when he was a child.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] His father wanted Alexander to join the priesthood and sent him to the Seminary School at Yekaterinburg.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] There he developed an interest in science and mathematics and instead of going on to Theology School in 1877 he enrolled at Saint Petersburg University, where he studied physics.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] After graduation with honors in 1882, he stayed on as a laboratory assistant at the university.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] However, the salary at the university was inadequate to support his family, and in 1883 he took a post as teacher and head of laboratory at the Russian Navy's Torpedo School in Kronstadt on Kotlin Island.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Along with his teaching duties at the naval school, Popov pursued related areas of research.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Trying to solve a problem with the failure in the electrical wire insulation on steel ships (which turned out to be a problem with electrical resonance) led him to further explore oscillations of high-requency electrical currents.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] His interest in this area of study (including the new field of "Hertzian" or radio waves) was intensified by his trip in 1893 to the Chicago World's Columbian Exposition in the United States, where he was able to confer with other researchers in the field.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Popov also read an 1894 article about British physicist Oliver Lodge's experiments related to the discovery of radio waves by German physicist Heinrich Hertz 6 years earlier.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] On 1 June 1894, after the death of Hertz, British physicist Oliver Lodge gave a memorial lecture on Hertz experiments.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] He set up a demonstration on the quasi optical nature of Hertzian waves (radio waves) and demonstrated their transmission at distances up to 50 meters.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Lodge used a detector called a *coherer*, a glass tube containing metal filings between two electrodes.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] When received waves from an antenna were applied to the electrodes, the coherer became conductive allowing the current from a battery to pass through it, with the impulse being picked up by a mirror galvanometer.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] After receiving a signal, the metal filings in the coherer had to be reset by a manually operated vibrator or by the vibrations of a bell placed on the table nearby that rang every time a transmission was received.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Popov set to work to design a more sensitive radio wave receiver that could be used as a lightning detector, to warn of thunderstorms by detecting the electromagnetic pulses of lightning strikes using a coherer receiver.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In Popov's lightning detector the coherer (*C*) was connected to an antenna (*A*), and to a separate circuit with a relay (*R*) and battery (*V*) which operated an electric bell (*B*).
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] The radio noise generated by a lightning strike turned on the coherer, the current from the battery was applied to the relay, closing its contacts, which applied current to the electromagnet (*E*) of the bell, pulling the arm over to ring the bell.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Popov added an innovative automatic reset feature of a "self tapping" coherer where the bell arm would spring back and tap the coherer, restoring it to its receptive state.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] The two chokes (*L*) in the coherer's leads prevented the radio signal across the coherer from short circuiting by passing through the DC circuit.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] He connected his receiver to a wire antenna (*A*) suspended high in the air and to a ground (earth) (*G*).
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] The antenna idea may have been based on a lightning rod and was an early use of a monopole wire aerial.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] On 7 May 1895 Popov presented the paper "*On the Relation of Metallic Powders to Electric Oscillations*", which described his lightning detector, to the Russian Physical and Chemical Society in St.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Most Eastern sources regard Popov's lightning detector as the first radio receiver, and 7 May has been celebrated since 1945 in the Russian Federation as "Radio Day".
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] However, there is no evidence Popov sent any type of message on that occasion.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Historian Charles Susskind in 1962 concluded that Popov did not use radio waves for actual wireless communication before mid-1896.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In 1895 Italian inventor Guglielmo Marconi began work on a purpose-built wireless telegraphy system based on "Hertzian" (radio) waves, developing a spark-gap transmitter and a much improved automatically reset coherer receiver.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] By mid-1895 Marconi had transmitted messages 1/2 mile (800 meters).
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] He then came up with the idea grounding his transmitter as well as his receiver, and by mid-1896 he was transmitting radio messages a mile and a half (2400 meters).
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Popov and Marconi's early work seems to have been done without knowledge of each other's system, although reading Marconi's June 1896 patent disclosures led Popov to develop a long-range wireless telegraphy system.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] His paper on his experiments: "On the relation of metallic powders to electrical oscillations", was published 15 December 1895.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] He did not apply for a patent for his invention.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In July 1895 he installed his receiver and a siphon recorder on the roof of the Institute of Forestry building in St.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Petersburg. and was able to detect thunderstorms at a range of 50 km, however he was also aware of its communication potential.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In 1896, the article depicting Popov's invention was reprinted in the 'Journal of the Russian Physical and Chemical Society'.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In March 1896, he effected transmission of radio waves between different campus buildings in St.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In November 1897, the French entrepreneur Eugène Ducretet made a transmitter and receiver based on wireless telegraphy in his own laboratory.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] According to Ducretet, he built his devices using Popov's lightning detector as a model.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] By 1898 Ducretet was manufacturing equipment of wireless telegraphy based on Popov's instructions.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] At the same time Popov effected ship-to-shore communication over a distance of 6 miles in 1898 and 30 miles in 1899.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In 1900 a radio station was established under Popov's instructions on Hogland island (Suursaari) to provide two-way communication by wireless telegraphy between the Russian naval base and the crew of the battleship *General-Admiral Apraksin*.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] The battleship had run aground on Hogland island in the Gulf of Finland in November 1899.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] The crew of the *Apraksin* were not in immediate danger, but the water in the Gulf began to freeze.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Due to bad weather and bureaucratic red tape, the crew of *Apraksin* did not arrive until January 1900 to establish a wireless station on Hogland Island.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] By 5 February, however, messages were being received reliably.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] The wireless messages were relayed to Hogland Island by a station some 25 miles away at Kymi (nowadays Kotka) on the Finnish coast.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Kotka was selected as the location for the wireless relay station because it was the point closest to Hogland Island served by telegraph wires connected to Russian naval headquarters.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] By the time the *Apraksin* was freed from the rocks by the icebreaker *Yermak* at the end of April, 440 official telegraph messages had been handled by the Hogland Island wireless station.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Besides the rescue of the Apraksin's crew, more than 50 Finnish fishermen, who were stranded on a piece of drift ice in the Gulf of Finland, were saved by the icebreaker *Yermak* following distress telegrams sent by wireless telegraphy.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In 1901 Alexander Popov was appointed as professor at the Electrotechnical Institute.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In 1905 he was elected director of the institute.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In 1905 he became seriously ill and died of a brain hemorrhage on 13 January 1906.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] He was succeeded as head of the Russian national wireless organisation by Simeon Aisenstein with whom he had worked closely.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In 1945 on the 50th anniversary of Popov's experiment the old Soviet Union made 7 May a new holiday, Radio Day, the day they claim Popov invented radio.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Historians note this holiday may be more due to Cold War era politics than historical evidence.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Radio Day is still officially marked in Russia and Bulgaria.
