[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Alexander Popov (film) is a 1949 biographical film about the life and work of Alexander Stepanovich Popov.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] In 1984, the USSR State Bank issued a jubilee coin with a face value of 1 ruble dedicated to A.S.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Many stamps have been issued depict A.S.Popov bearing the honor of him inventing radio.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Some of his descendants escaped to Manchuria during the Bolshevik Revolution and eventually made their way to the United States.
[src:transmission-line/alexander-stepanovich-popov] Paul Popov, who became a prominent physician in San Francisco and Paul's son, Egor Popov (1913–2001), who became a UC Berkeley Professor Emeritus of Civil and Environmental Engineering.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The **Advanced Research Projects Agency Network** (**ARPANET**) was the first wide-area packet-switched network with distributed control and one of the first computer networks to implement the TCP/IP protocol suite.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Both technologies became the technical foundation of the Internet.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The ARPANET was established by the Advanced Research Projects Agency (now DARPA) of the United States Department of Defense.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Licklider, Bob Taylor initiated the ARPANET project in 1966 to enable resource sharing between remote computers.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Taylor appointed Larry Roberts as program manager.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Roberts made the key decisions about the request for proposal to build the network.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] He incorporated Donald Davies' concepts and designs for packet switching, and sought input from Paul Baran.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In 1969, ARPA awarded the contract to build the Interface Message Processors (IMPs) for the network to Bolt Beranek & Newman (BBN).
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The design was led by Bob Kahn who developed the first protocol for the network.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Roberts engaged Leonard Kleinrock at UCLA to develop mathematical methods for analyzing the packet network technology.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The first computers were connected in 1969 and the Network Control Program was implemented in 1970, development of which was led by Steve Crocker at UCLA and other graduate students, including Jon Postel.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The network was declared operational in 1971.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Further software development enabled remote login and file transfer, which was used to provide an early form of email.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The network expanded rapidly and operational control passed to the Defense Communications Agency in 1975.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Bob Kahn moved to DARPA and, together with Vint Cerf at Stanford University, formulated the Transmission Control Program for internetworking.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] As this work progressed, a protocol was developed by which multiple separate networks could be joined into a network of networks; this incorporated concepts pioneered in the French CYCLADES project directed by Louis Pouzin and the ideas of Bob Metcalfe at Xerox Parc.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Version 4 of TCP/IP was installed in the ARPANET for production use on January 1, 1983, after the Department of Defense made it standard for all military computer networking.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Access to the ARPANET was expanded in 1981 when the National Science Foundation (NSF) funded the Computer Science Network (CSNET).
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In the early 1980s, the NSF funded the establishment of national supercomputing centers at several universities and provided network access and network interconnectivity with the NSFNET project in 1986.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The ARPANET was formally decommissioned in 1990, after partnerships with the telecommunication and computer industry had assured private sector expansion and commercialization of an expanded worldwide network, known as the Internet.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Historically, voice and data communications were based on methods of circuit switching, as exemplified in the traditional telephone network, wherein each telephone call is allocated a dedicated end-to-end electronic connection between the two communicating stations.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The connection is established by switching systems that connected multiple intermediate call legs between these systems for the duration of the call.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The traditional model of the circuit-switched telecommunication network was challenged in the early 1960s by Paul Baran at the RAND Corporation, who had been researching systems that could sustain operation during partial destruction, such as by nuclear war.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] He developed the theoretical model of *distributed adaptive message block switching*.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] However, the telecommunication establishment rejected the development in favor of existing models.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Donald Davies at the United Kingdom's National Physical Laboratory (NPL) independently arrived at a similar concept in 1965.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The earliest ideas for a computer network intended to allow general communications among computer users were formulated by computer scientist J.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Licklider of Bolt Beranek and Newman (BBN), in April 1963, in memoranda discussing the concept of the "Intergalactic Computer Network".
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Those ideas encompassed many of the features of the contemporary Internet.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In October 1963, Licklider was appointed head of the Behavioral Sciences and Command and Control programs at the Defense Department's Advanced Research Projects Agency (ARPA).
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] He convinced Ivan Sutherland and Bob Taylor that this network concept was very important and merited development, although Licklider left ARPA before any contracts were assigned for development.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Sutherland and Taylor continued their interest in creating the network, in part, to allow ARPA-sponsored researchers at various corporate and academic locales to utilize computers provided by ARPA, and, in part, to quickly distribute new software and other computer science results.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Taylor recalls the circumstance: "For each of these three terminals, I had three different sets of user commands.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] So, if I was talking online with someone at S.D.C., and I wanted to talk to someone I knew at Berkeley, or M.I.T., about this, I had to get up from the S.D.C. terminal, go over and log into the other terminal and get in touch with them.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] I said, 'Oh Man!', it's obvious what to do: If you have these three terminals, there ought to be one terminal that goes anywhere you want to go.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Donald Davies' work caught the attention of ARPANET developers at the Symposium on Operating Systems Principles in October 1967.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] He gave the first public presentation, having coined the term *packet switching*, in August 1968 and incorporated it into the NPL network in England.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The NPL network, followed by the ARPANET, were the first two networks in the world to implement packet switching.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Roberts said the computer networks built in the 1970s were similar "in nearly all respects" to Davies' original 1965 design.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In February 1966, Bob Taylor successfully lobbied ARPA's Director Charles M.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Herzfeld redirected funds in the amount of one million dollars from a ballistic missile defense program to Taylor's budget.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Taylor hired Larry Roberts as a program manager in the ARPA Information Processing Techniques Office in January 1967 to work on the ARPANET.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Roberts met Paul Baran in February 1967, but did not discuss networks.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The initial standards for identification and authentication of users, transmission of characters, and error checking and retransmission procedures were discussed.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Roberts' proposal was that all mainframe computers would connect to one another directly.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The other investigators were reluctant to dedicate these computing resources to network administration.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] After the design session, Wesley Clark proposed minicomputers should be used as an interface to create a message switching network.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Roberts modified the ARPANET plan to incorporate Clark's suggestion and named the minicomputers Interface Message Processors (IMPs).
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The plan was presented at the inaugural Symposium on Operating Systems Principles in October 1967.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Donald Davies' work on packet switching and the NPL network, presented by a colleague (Roger Scantlebury), and that of Paul Baran, came to the attention of the ARPA investigators at this conference.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Roberts applied Davies' concept of packet switching for the ARPANET, and sought input from Paul Baran on dynamic routing.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The NPL network was using line speeds of 768 kbit/s, and the proposed line speed for the ARPANET was upgraded from 2.4 kbit/s to 50 kbit/s.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] By mid-1968, Roberts and Barry Wessler wrote a final version of the IMP specification based on a Stanford Research Institute (SRI) report that ARPA commissioned to write detailed specifications describing the ARPANET communications network.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Roberts gave a report to Taylor on 3 June, who approved it on 21 June.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] After approval by ARPA, a Request for Quotation (RFQ) was issued for 140 potential bidders.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Most computer science companies regarded the ARPA proposal as outlandish, and only twelve submitted bids to build a network; of the twelve, ARPA regarded only four as top-rank contractors.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] At year's end, ARPA considered only two contractors and awarded the contract to build the network to BBN in January 1969.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The initial, seven-person BBN team were much aided by the technical specificity of their response to the ARPA RFQ, and thus quickly produced the first working system.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The "IMP guys" were led by Frank Heart; the theoretical design of the network was led by Bob Kahn; the team included Dave Walden, Severo Ornstein, William Crowther and several others.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The BBN-proposed network closely followed Roberts' ARPA plan: a network composed of small computers, the IMPs (similar to the later concept of routers), that functioned as gateways interconnecting local resources.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Routing, flow control, software design and network control were developed by the BBN team.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] At each site, the IMPs performed store-and-forward packet switching functions and were interconnected with leased lines via telecommunication data sets (modems), with initial data rates of 50kbit/s.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The host computers were connected to the IMPs via custom serial communication interfaces.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The system, including the hardware and the packet switching software, was designed and installed in nine months.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The BBN team continued to interact with the NPL team with meetings between them taking place in the U.S. and the U.K.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] As with the NPL network, the first-generation IMPs were built using a rugged computer version of the Honeywell DDP-516 computer, configured with 24KB of expandable magnetic-core memory, and a 16-channel Direct Multiplex Control (DMC) direct memory access unit.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The DMC established custom interfaces with each of the host computers and modems.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In addition to the front-panel lamps, the DDP-516 computer also features a special set of 24 indicator lamps showing the status of the IMP communication channels.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Each IMP could support up to four local hosts and could communicate with up to six remote IMPs via early Digital Signal 0 leased telephone lines.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The network connected one computer in Utah with three in California.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Later, the Department of Defense allowed the universities to join the network for sharing hardware and software resources.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The first four nodes were designated as a testbed for developing and debugging the 1822 protocol, which was a major undertaking.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] While they were connected electronically in 1969, network applications were not possible until the Network Control Program was implemented in 1970 enabling the first two host-host protocols, remote login (Telnet) and file transfer (FTP) which were specified and implemented between 1969 and 1973.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Network traffic began to grow once email was established at the majority of sites by around 1973.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The initial ARPANET configuration linked UCLA, ARC, UCSB, and the University of Utah School of Computing.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The first node was created at UCLA, where Leonard Kleinrock could evaluate network performance and examine his theories on message delay.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The first successful host-to-host connection on the ARPANET was made between Stanford Research Institute (SRI) and UCLA, by SRI programmer Bill Duvall and UCLA student programmer Charley Kline, at 10:30 pm PST on 29 October 1969 (6:30 UTC on 30 October 1969).
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Kline connected from UCLA's SDS Sigma 7 Host computer (in Boelter Hall room 3420) to the Stanford Research Institute's SDS 940 Host computer.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Kline typed the command "login," but initially the SDS 940 crashed after he typed two characters.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] About an hour later, after Duvall adjusted parameters on the machine, Kline tried again and successfully logged in.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Hence, the first two characters successfully transmitted over the ARPANET were "lo".
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The first permanent ARPANET link was established on 21 November 1969, between the IMP at UCLA and the IMP at the Stanford Research Institute.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] By 5 December 1969, the initial four-node network was established.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Elizabeth Feinler created the first Resource Handbook for ARPANET in 1969 which led to the development of the ARPANET directory.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The directory, built by Feinler and a team made it possible to navigate the ARPANET.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In 1968, Roberts contracted with Kleinrock to measure the performance of the network and find areas for improvement.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Building on his earlier work on queueing theory and optimization of message delay in communication networks, Kleinrock specified mathematical models of the performance of packet-switched networks, which underpinned the development of the ARPANET as it expanded rapidly in the early 1970s.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Analytic methods had limitations, and computer simulation studies were also employed by ARPA, and at the NPL in the United Kingdom.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Roberts engaged Howard Frank to consult on the topological design of the network.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Frank made recommendations to increase throughput and reduce costs in a scaled-up network.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] By March 1970, the ARPANET reached the East Coast of the United States, when an IMP at BBN in Cambridge, Massachusetts was connected to the network.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Thereafter, the ARPANET grew: 9 IMPs by June 1970 and 13 IMPs by December 1970, then 18 by September 1971 (when the network included 23 university and government hosts); 29 IMPs by August 1972, and 40 by September 1973.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] By June 1974, there were 46 IMPs, and in July 1975, the network numbered 57 IMPs.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] By 1981, the number was 213 host computers, with another host connecting approximately every twenty days.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Support for inter-IMP circuits of up to 230.4 kbit/s was added in 1970, although considerations of cost and IMP processing power meant this capability was not actively used.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Larry Roberts saw the ARPANET and NPL projects as complementary and sought in 1970 to connect them via a satellite link.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Peter Kirstein's research group at University College London (UCL) was subsequently chosen in 1971 in place of NPL for the UK connection.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In June 1973, a transatlantic satellite link connected ARPANET to the Norwegian Seismic Array (NORSAR), via the Tanum Earth Station in Sweden, and onward via a terrestrial circuit to a TIP at UCL.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] UCL provided a gateway for interconnection of the ARPANET with British academic networks, the first international resource sharing network, and carried out some of the earliest experimental research work on internetworking.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] 1971 saw the start of the use of the non-ruggedized (and therefore significantly lighter) Honeywell 316 as an IMP.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] It could also be configured as a Terminal Interface Processor (TIP), which provided terminal server support for up to 63 ASCII serial terminals through a multi-line controller in place of one of the hosts.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The 316 featured a greater degree of integration than the 516, which made it less expensive and easier to maintain.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The 316 was configured with 40 kB of core memory for a TIP.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The size of core memory was later increased to 32 kB for the IMPs, and 56 kB for TIPs, in 1973.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The ARPANET was demonstrated at the International Conference on Computer Communications (ICCC) in October 1972.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In 1975, BBN introduced IMP software running on the Pluribus multi-processor.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In 1981, BBN introduced IMP software running on its own C/30 processor product.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Because it was never a goal for the ARPANET to support IMPs from vendors other than BBN, the IMP-to-IMP protocol and message format were not standardized.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] However, the IMPs did nonetheless communicate amongst themselves to perform link-state routing, to do reliable forwarding of messages, and to provide remote monitoring and management functions to ARPANET's Network Control Center.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Initially, each IMP had a 6-bit identifier and supported up to 4 hosts, which were identified with a 2-bit index.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] An upgrade in early 1976 extended the host and IMP numbering to 8-bit and 16-bit, respectively.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In addition to primary routing and forwarding responsibilities, the IMP ran several background programs, titled TTY, DEBUG, PARAMETER-CHANGE, DISCARD, TRACE, and STATISTICS.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] These were given host numbers in order to be addressed directly and provided functions independently of any connected host.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] For example, "TTY" allowed an on-site operator to send ARPANET packets manually via the teletype connected directly to the IMP.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The starting point for host-to-host communication on the ARPANET in 1969 was the 1822 protocol, which defined the transmission of messages to an IMP.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The message format was designed to work unambiguously with a broad range of computer architectures.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] An 1822 message essentially consisted of a message type, a numeric host address, and a data field.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] To send a data message to another host, the transmitting host formatted a data message containing the destination host's address and the data message being sent, and then transmitted the message through the 1822 hardware interface.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The IMP then delivered the message to its destination address, either by delivering it to a locally connected host or by delivering it to another IMP.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] When the message was ultimately delivered to the destination host, the receiving IMP would transmit a *Ready for Next Message* (RFNM) acknowledgment to the sending, host IMP.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Unlike modern Internet datagrams, the ARPANET was designed to reliably transmit 1822 messages, and to inform the host computer when it loses a message; the contemporary IP is unreliable, whereas the TCP is reliable.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Nonetheless, the 1822 protocol proved inadequate for handling multiple connections among different applications residing in a host computer.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] This problem was addressed with the Network Control Program (NCP), which provided a standard method to establish reliable, flow-controlled, bidirectional communications links among different processes in different host computers.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The NCP interface allowed application software to connect across the ARPANET by implementing higher-level communication protocols, an early example of the *protocol layering* concept later incorporated in the OSI model.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] NCP was developed under the leadership of Steve Crocker, then a graduate student at UCLA.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Crocker created and led the Network Working Group (NWG) which was made up of a collection of graduate students at universities and research laboratories, including Jon Postel at UCLA.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] They were sponsored by ARPA to carry out the development of the ARPANET and the software for the host computers that supported applications.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Beginning in 1972, Louis Pouzin and Hubert Zimmermann at the IRIA in France pioneered a simplified end-to-end approach to networking that they called a catenet, which was discussed at the ICCC.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Bob Kahn left BBN in 1972, briefly to be President of Telenet, and then moved to DARPA, first as program manager for the ARPANET, under Larry Roberts, then as director of the IPTO when Roberts left to be President of Telenet.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Kahn worked on both satellite packet networks and ground-based radio packet networks, and recognized the value of being able to communicate across both.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Steve Crocker, now at DARPA, and the leaders of British and French network projects founded the International Network Working Group (INWG) and, on Crocker's recommendation, Vint Cerf, now on the faculty at Stanford University, became its Chair.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Bob Metcalfe developed the theory and practice behind Ethernet and the PARC Universal Packet.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] These groups considered how to interconnect packet switching networks with different specifications, that is, internetworking.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Peter Kirstein put internetworking into practice at University College London in 1973.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Research led by Kahn and Cerf resulted in the formulation of the Transmission Control Program in 1974.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Its specification was written by Cerf with Yogen Dalal and Carl Sunshine at Stanford in December that year (RFC 675), and a group of researchers began publishing Internet Experiment Notes (IENs).
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The following year, testing began through concurrent implementations at Stanford, BBN and University College London.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] At first a monolithic design, the software was redesigned as a modular protocol stack in Version 4 in 1978, which reflected concepts from the French CYCLADES project directed by Pouzin and the ideas of Bob Metcalfe at Xerox Parc.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] This was installed in the ARPANET for production use in January 1983, replacing NCP.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The development of the complete Internet protocol suite by 1989, as outlined in RFC 1122 and RFC 1123, and partnerships with the telecommunication and computer industry laid the foundation for the adoption of TCP/IP as a comprehensive protocol suite as the core component of the emerging Internet.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] ARPA was intended to fund advanced research.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The ARPANET was a research project that was communications-oriented, rather than user-oriented in design.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Nonetheless, in the summer of 1975, operational control of the ARPANET passed to the Defense Communications Agency.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] At about this time, the first ARPANET encryption devices were deployed to support classified traffic.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The transatlantic connectivity with Norway (NORSAR and NDRE) and University College London (UCL) later evolved into the SATNET.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The ARPANET, SATNET and PRNET were interconnected in 1977.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The DoD made TCP/IP the standard communication protocol for all military computer networking in 1980.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Norway and UCL left the ARPANET and began using TCP/IP over SATNET in 1982.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] On January 1, 1983, known as flag day, TCP/IP protocols became the standard for the ARPANET, replacing the earlier Network Control Protocol.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In September 1984 work was completed on restructuring the ARPANET, giving U.S. military sites their own Military Network (MILNET) for unclassified defense department communications.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Both networks carried unclassified information and were connected at a small number of controlled gateways which would allow total separation in the event of an emergency.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] MILNET was part of the Defense Data Network (DDN).
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Separating the civil and military networks reduced the 113-node ARPANET by 68 nodes.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] After MILNET was split away, the ARPANET would continue to be used as an Internet backbone for researchers, but be slowly phased out.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] NCP provided a standard set of network services that could be shared by several applications running on a single host computer.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] This led to the evolution of *application protocols* that operated, more or less, independently of the underlying network service, and permitted independent advances in the underlying protocols.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The various application protocols, such as TELNET for remote time-sharing access and File Transfer Protocol (FTP), the latter used to enable rudimentary electronic mail, were developed and eventually ported to run over the TCP/IP protocol suite.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In the 1980s, FTP for email was replaced by the Simple Mail Transfer Protocol and, later, POP and IMAP.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Telnet was developed in 1969, beginning with RFC 15, extended in RFC 855.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The original specification for the File Transfer Protocol was written by Abhay Bhushan and published as RFC 114 on 16 April 1971.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] By 1973, the File Transfer Protocol (FTP) specification had been defined (RFC 354) and implemented, enabling file transfers over the ARPANET.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In 1971, Ray Tomlinson, of BBN sent the first network e-mail (RFC 524, RFC 561).
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] An ARPA study in 1973, a year after network e-mail was introduced to the ARPANET community, found that three-quarters of the traffic over the ARPANET consisted of email messages.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] E-mail remained a very large part of the overall ARPANET traffic.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The Network Voice Protocol (NVP) specifications were defined in 1977 (RFC 741), and implemented.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] But, because of technical shortcomings, conference calls over the ARPANET never worked well; the contemporary Voice over Internet Protocol (packet voice) was decades away.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The Purdy Polynomial hash algorithm was developed for the ARPANET to protect passwords in 1971 at the request of Larry Roberts, head of ARPA at that time.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] It computed a polynomial of degree 224 + 17 modulo the 64-bit prime *p* = 264 − 59.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The algorithm was later used by Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) to hash passwords in the VMS operating system and is still being used for this purpose.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Because of its government funding, certain forms of traffic were discouraged or prohibited.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Leonard Kleinrock claims to have committed the first illegal act on the Internet, having sent a request for return of his electric razor after a meeting in England in 1973.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] At the time, use of the ARPANET for personal reasons was unlawful.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In 1978, against the rules of the network, Gary Thuerk of Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) sent out the first mass email to approximately 400 potential clients via the ARPANET.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] He claims that this resulted in $13 million worth of sales in DEC products, and highlighted the potential of email marketing.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] In 1985, the NSF funded the establishment of national supercomputing centers at several universities and provided network access and network interconnectivity with the NSFNET project in 1986.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] NSFNET became the Internet backbone for government agencies and universities.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The ARPANET project was formally decommissioned in 1990.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The original IMPs and TIPs were phased out as the ARPANET was shut down after the introduction of the NSFNet, but some IMPs remained in service as late as July 1990.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The technological advancements and practical applications achieved through the ARPANET were instrumental in shaping modern computer networking including the Internet.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Development and implementation of the concepts of packet switching, decentralized networks, and communication protocols laid the foundation for a global network that revolutionized communication, information sharing and collaborative research across the world.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The ARPANET was related to many other research projects, which either influenced the ARPANET design, were ancillary projects, or spun out of the ARPANET.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Senator Al Gore authored the High Performance Computing and Communication Act of 1991, commonly referred to as "The Gore Bill", after hearing the 1988 concept for a National Research Network submitted to Congress by a group chaired by Leonard Kleinrock.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The bill was passed on 9 December 1991 and led to the National Information Infrastructure (NII), which Gore called the *information superhighway*.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The ARPANET project was honored with two IEEE Milestones, both dedicated in 2009.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] On May 17, 2011, Arlington County, Virginia, erected two historical markers commemorating the internet's roots at 1400 Wilson Boulevard, in its Rosslyn neighborhood, the agency's home from 1970 to 1975.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] The ARPANET used distributed computation and incorporated frequent re-computation of routing tables (automatic routing was technically challenging at the time).
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] These features increased the survivability of the network in the event of a significant interruption.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Furthermore, the ARPANET was designed to survive subordinate network losses.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Paul Baran, the first to put forward a theoretical model for communication using packet switching, conducted the RAND study referenced above.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Though the ARPANET did not exactly share Baran's project's goal, he said his work did contribute to the development of the ARPANET.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Minutes taken by Elmer Shapiro of Stanford Research Institute at the ARPANET design meeting of 9–10 October 1967 indicate that a version of Baran's routing method ("hot potato") may be used, consistent with the NPL team's proposal at the Symposium on Operating System Principles in Gatlinburg.
[src:transmission-line/arpanet] Later, in the 1970s, ARPA did emphasize the goal of "command and control".
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] In electrical engineering, a **transmission line** is a specialized cable or other structure designed to conduct electromagnetic waves in a contained manner.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The term applies when the conductors are long enough that the wave nature of the transmission must be taken into account.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] This applies especially to radio-frequency engineering because the short wavelengths mean that wave phenomena arise over very short distances (this can be as short as millimetres depending on frequency).
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] However, the theory of transmission lines was historically developed to explain phenomena on very long telegraph lines, especially submarine telegraph cables.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] RF engineers commonly use short pieces of transmission line, usually in the form of printed planar transmission lines, arranged in certain patterns to build circuits such as filters.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] These circuits, known as distributed-element circuits, are an alternative to traditional circuits using discrete capacitors and inductors.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Ordinary electrical cables suffice to carry low frequency alternating current (AC), such as mains power, which reverses direction 100 to 120 times per second, and audio signals.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] However, they are not generally used to carry currents in the radio frequency range, above about 30 kHz, because the energy tends to radiate off the cable as radio waves, causing power losses.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Radio frequency currents also tend to reflect from discontinuities in the cable such as connectors and joints, and travel back down the cable toward the source.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] These reflections act as bottlenecks, preventing the signal power from reaching the destination.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Transmission lines use specialized construction, and impedance matching, to carry electromagnetic signals with minimal reflections and power losses.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The distinguishing feature of most transmission lines is that they have uniform cross sectional dimensions along their length, giving them a uniform impedance, called the *characteristic impedance*, to prevent reflections.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Types of transmission line include parallel line (ladder line, twisted pair), coaxial cable, and planar transmission lines such as stripline and microstrip.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The higher the frequency of electromagnetic waves moving through a given cable or medium, the shorter the wavelength of the waves.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Transmission lines become necessary when the transmitted frequency's wavelength is sufficiently short that the length of the cable becomes a significant part of a wavelength.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] At frequencies of microwave and higher, power losses in transmission lines become excessive, and waveguides are used instead, which function as "pipes" to confine and guide the electromagnetic waves.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Some sources define waveguides as a type of transmission line; however, this article will not include them.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Mathematical analysis of the behaviour of electrical transmission lines grew out of the work of James Clerk Maxwell, Lord Kelvin, and Oliver Heaviside.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] In 1855, Lord Kelvin formulated a diffusion model of the current in a submarine cable.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The model correctly predicted the poor performance of the 1858 trans-Atlantic submarine telegraph cable.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] In 1885, Heaviside published the first papers that described his analysis of propagation in cables and the modern form of the telegrapher's equations.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] In the simplest case, the network is assumed to be linear (i.e. the complex voltage across either port is proportional to the complex current flowing into it when there are no reflections), and the two ports are assumed to be interchangeable.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Typical values of $Z_{0}$ are 50 or 75 ohms for a coaxial cable, about 100 ohms for a twisted pair of wires, and about 300 ohms for a common type of untwisted pair used in radio transmission.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Propagation delay is proportional to the length of the transmission line and is never less than the length divided by the speed of light.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Typical delays for modern communication transmission lines vary from 3.33 ns/m to 5 ns/m.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] When sending power down a transmission line, it is usually desirable that as much power as possible will be absorbed by the load and as little as possible will be reflected back to the source.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] This can be ensured by making the load impedance equal to $Z_{0}$ , in which case the transmission line is said to be *matched*.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Some of the power that is fed into a transmission line is lost because of its resistance.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] This effect is called *ohmic* or *resistive* loss (see ohmic heating).
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] At high frequencies, another effect called *dielectric loss* becomes significant, adding to the losses caused by resistance.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Dielectric loss is caused when the insulating material inside the transmission line absorbs energy from the alternating electric field and converts it to heat (see dielectric heating).
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The transmission line is modelled with a resistance ( R ) and inductance ( L ) in series with a capacitance ( C ) and conductance ( G ) in parallel.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The resistance and conductance contribute to the loss in a transmission line.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The total loss of power in a transmission line is often specified in decibels per metre (dB/m), and always depends on the frequency of the signal.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The manufacturer often supplies a chart showing the loss in dB/m at a range of frequencies.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] A loss of 3 dB corresponds approximately to a halving of the power.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Propagation delay is often specified in units of nanoseconds per metre.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] While propagation delay usually depends on the frequency of the signal, transmission lines are typically operated over frequency ranges where the propagation delay is approximately constant.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The **telegrapher's equations** (or just **telegraph equations**) are a pair of linear differential equations which describe the voltage ( V ) and current ( I ) on an electrical transmission line with distance and time.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] They were developed by Oliver Heaviside who created the *transmission line model*, and are based on Maxwell's equations.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The transmission line model is an example of the distributed-element model.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The model consists of an *infinite series* of the elements shown in the figure, and the values of the components are specified *per unit length* so the picture of the component can be misleading.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] R , L , C , and G may also be functions of frequency.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] An alternative notation is to use $R'$ , $L'$ , $C'$ and $G'$ to emphasize that the values are derivatives with respect to length.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] These quantities can also be known as the primary line constants to distinguish from the secondary line constants derived from them, these being the propagation constant, attenuation constant and phase constant.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] When the elements R and G are negligibly small the transmission line is considered as a lossless structure.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] In this hypothetical case, the model depends only on the L and C elements which greatly simplifies the analysis.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] These are wave equations which have plane waves with equal propagation speed in the forward and reverse directions as solutions.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The physical significance of this is that electromagnetic waves propagate down transmission lines and in general, there is a reflected component that interferes with the original signal.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] These equations are fundamental to transmission line theory.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] where $\gamma$ is the (complex) propagation constant.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] They are also wave equations, and have solutions similar to the special case, but which are a mixture of sines and cosines with exponential decay factors.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The constants $V_{(\pm )}$ must be determined from boundary conditions.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] where atan2 is the everywhere-defined form of two-parameter arctangent function, with arbitrary value zero when both arguments are zero.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] with the plus or minus signs chosen opposite to the direction of the wave's motion through the conducting medium.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] If R, G, L, and C are constants that are *not* frequency dependent and the Heaviside condition is met, then waves travel down the transmission line without phase distortion.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The characteristic impedance $Z_{0}$ of a transmission line is the ratio of the amplitude of a *single* voltage wave to its current wave.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Since most transmission lines also have a reflected wave, the characteristic impedance is generally not the impedance that is measured on the line.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] where $\gamma$ is the propagation constant and ${\mathit {\Gamma }}_{\mathrm {L} }={\frac {\,Z_{\mathrm {L} }-Z_{0}\,}{Z_{\mathrm {L} }+Z_{0}}}$ is the voltage reflection coefficient measured at the load end of the transmission line.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] In calculating $\beta ,$ the wavelength is generally different *inside* the transmission line to what it would be in free-space.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Consequently, the velocity factor of the material the transmission line is made of needs to be taken into account when doing such a calculation.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] for all $n\,.$ This includes the case when $n=0$ , meaning that the length of the transmission line is negligibly small compared to the wavelength.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The physical significance of this is that the transmission line can be ignored (i.e. treated as a wire) in either case.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Transmission lines are mainly defined in using ABCD parameters or transmission parameters.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] As $A=D$ , the transmission lines are symmetric networks.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] It also satisfies reciprocity condition $AD-BC=1$ .
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Since transmission lines are electrically passive and symmetric devices, Y12 = Y21, and Y11 = Y22.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Impedance (Z) parameters are defined by applying a fixed current into one port (I1) of a transmission line with the other port open and measuring the resulting voltage on each port (V1, V2) and computing the impedance parameter Z11 is V1/I1, and the impedance parameter Z12 is V2/I1.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Since transmission lines are electrically passive and symmetric devices, V12 = V21, and V11 = V22.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Unlike ideal lumped 2 port elements (resistors, capacitors, inductors, etc.) which do not have defined Z parameters, transmission lines have an internal path to ground, which permits the definition of Z parameters.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Scattering (S) matrix parameters model the electrical behavior of the transmission line with matched loads at each termination.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] For lossless and lossy transmission lines respectively, the S parameter matrix is as follows, using standard hyperbolic to circular complex translations.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Transmission lines may be placed in proximity to each other such that they electrically interact, such as two microstrip lines in close proximity.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Such transmission lines are said to be coupled transmission lines.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Coupled transmission lines are characterized by an even and odd mode analysis.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The even mode is characterized by excitation of the two conductors with a signal of equal amplitude and phase.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The odd mode is characterized by excitation with signals of equal and opposite magnitude.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The even and odd modes each have their own characteristic impedances ( $Z_{0e}$ , $Z_{0o}$ ) and phase constants ( $\beta _{e}{\text{, }}\beta _{o}$ ).
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Lossy coupled transmission lines have their own even and odd mode attenuation constants ( $\alpha _{e}{\text{, }}\alpha _{o}$ ), which in turn leads to even and odd mode propagation constants ( $\gamma _{e}{\text{, }}\gamma _{o}$ ).
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Coaxial lines confine virtually all of the electromagnetic wave to the area inside the cable.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Coaxial lines can therefore be bent and twisted (subject to limits) without negative effects, and they can be strapped to conductive supports without inducing unwanted currents in them.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] However, at frequencies for which the wavelength (in the dielectric) is significantly shorter than the circumference of the cable other transverse modes can propagate.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] These modes are classified into two groups, transverse electric (TE) and transverse magnetic (TM) waveguide modes.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] When more than one mode can exist, bends and other irregularities in the cable geometry can cause power to be transferred from one mode to another.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The most common use for coaxial cables is for television and other signals with bandwidth of multiple megahertz.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] In the middle 20th century they carried long distance telephone connections.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Planar transmission lines are transmission lines with conductors, or in some cases dielectric strips, that are flat, ribbon-shaped lines.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] They are used to interconnect components on printed circuits and integrated circuits working at microwave frequencies because the planar type fits in well with the manufacturing methods for these components.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Several forms of planar transmission lines exist.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] A microstrip circuit uses a thin flat conductor which is parallel to a ground plane.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Microstrip can be made by having a strip of copper on one side of a printed circuit board (PCB) or ceramic substrate while the other side is a continuous ground plane.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The width of the strip, the thickness of the insulating layer (PCB or ceramic) and the dielectric constant of the insulating layer determine the characteristic impedance.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Microstrip is an open structure whereas coaxial cable is a closed structure.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] A stripline circuit uses a flat strip of metal which is sandwiched between two parallel ground planes.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The insulating material of the substrate forms a dielectric.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The width of the strip, the thickness of the substrate and the relative permittivity of the substrate determine the characteristic impedance of the strip which is a transmission line.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] A coplanar waveguide consists of a center strip and two adjacent outer conductors, all three of them flat structures that are deposited onto the same insulating substrate and thus are located in the same plane ("coplanar").
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The width of the center conductor, the distance between inner and outer conductors, and the relative permittivity of the substrate determine the characteristic impedance of the coplanar transmission line.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] A balanced line is a transmission line consisting of two conductors of the same type, and equal impedance to ground and other circuits.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] There are many formats of balanced lines, amongst the most common are twisted pair, star quad and twin-lead.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Twisted pairs are commonly used for terrestrial telephone communications.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] In such cables, many pairs are grouped together in a single cable, from two to several thousand.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The format is also used for data network distribution inside buildings, but the cable is more expensive because the transmission line parameters are tightly controlled.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Star quad is a four-conductor cable in which all four conductors are twisted together around the cable axis.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] It is sometimes used for two circuits, such as 4-wire telephony and other telecommunications applications.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] In this configuration each pair uses two non-adjacent conductors.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Other times it is used for a single, balanced line, such as audio applications and 2-wire telephony.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] In this configuration two non-adjacent conductors are terminated together at both ends of the cable, and the other two conductors are also terminated together.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] When used for two circuits, crosstalk is reduced relative to cables with two separate twisted pairs.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] When used for a single, balanced line, magnetic interference picked up by the cable arrives as a virtually perfect common mode signal, which is easily removed by coupling transformers.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The combined benefits of twisting, balanced signalling, and quadrupole pattern give outstanding noise immunity, especially advantageous for low signal level applications such as microphone cables, even when installed very close to a power cable.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The disadvantage is that star quad, in combining two conductors, typically has double the capacitance of similar two-conductor twisted and shielded audio cable.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] High capacitance causes increasing distortion and greater loss of high frequencies as distance increases.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Twin-lead consists of a pair of conductors held apart by a continuous insulator.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] By holding the conductors a known distance apart, the geometry is fixed and the line characteristics are reliably consistent.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] It is lower loss than coaxial cable because the characteristic impedance of twin-lead is generally higher than coaxial cable, leading to lower resistive losses due to the reduced current.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] However, it is more susceptible to interference.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Lecher lines are a form of parallel conductor that can be used at UHF for creating resonant circuits.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] They are a convenient practical format that fills the gap between lumped components (used at HF/VHF) and resonant cavities (used at UHF/SHF).
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Unbalanced lines were formerly much used for telegraph transmission, but this form of communication has now fallen into disuse.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Cables are similar to twisted pair in that many cores are bundled into the same cable but only one conductor is provided per circuit and there is no twisting.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] All the circuits on the same route use a common path for the return current (earth return).
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] There is a power transmission version of single-wire earth return in use in many locations.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Electrical transmission lines are very widely used to transmit high frequency signals over long or short distances with minimum power loss.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] One familiar example is the down lead from a TV or radio aerial to the receiver.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] A large variety of circuits can also be constructed with transmission lines including impedance matching circuits, filters, power dividers and directional couplers.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] A stepped transmission line is used for broad range impedance matching.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] It can be considered as multiple transmission line segments connected in series, with the characteristic impedance of each individual element to be $Z_{\mathrm {0,i} }$ .
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] where $\beta _{\mathrm {i} }$ is the wave number of the $\mathrm {i}$ -th transmission line segment and $\ell _{\mathrm {i} }$ is the length of this segment, and $Z_{\mathrm {i} }$ is the front-end impedance that loads the $\mathrm {i}$ -th segment.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] At higher frequencies, the reactive parasitic effects of real world lumped elements, including inductors and capacitors, limits their usefulness.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Therefore, it is sometimes useful to approximate the electrical characteristics of inductors and capacitors with transmission lines at the higher frequencies using Richards' transformations and then substitute the transmission lines for the lumped elements.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] More accurate forms of multimode high frequency inductor modeling with transmission lines exist for advanced designers.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] If a short-circuited or open-circuited transmission line is wired in parallel with a line used to transfer signals from point A to point B, then it will function as a filter.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The method for making stubs is similar to the method for using Lecher lines for crude frequency measurement, but it is 'working backwards'.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] One method recommended in the RSGB's radiocommunication handbook is to take an open-circuited length of transmission line wired in parallel with the feeder delivering signals from an aerial.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] By cutting the free end of the transmission line, a minimum in the strength of the signal observed at a receiver can be found.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] At this stage the stub filter will reject this frequency and the odd harmonics, but if the free end of the stub is shorted then the stub will become a filter rejecting the even harmonics.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Wideband filters can be achieved using multiple stubs.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] However, this is a somewhat dated technique.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Much more compact filters can be made with other methods such as parallel-line resonators.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] Transmission lines are used as pulse generators.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] By charging the transmission line and then discharging it into a resistive load, a rectangular pulse equal in length to twice the electrical length of the line can be obtained, although with half the voltage.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] A Blumlein transmission line is a related pulse forming device that overcomes this limitation.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] These are sometimes used as the pulsed power sources for radar transmitters and other devices.
[src:transmission-line/transmission-line] The theory of sound wave propagation is very similar mathematically to that of electromagnetic waves, so techniques from transmission line theory are also used to build structures to conduct acoustic waves; and these are called acoustic transmission lines.
